171
00:08:22,250 --> 00:08:23,889
This question comes from...

172
00:08:23,889 --> 00:08:24,889
Justin:

173
00:08:24,889 --> 00:08:26,771
“There seems to be signs that Hong Kong

174
00:08:26,771 --> 00:08:29,240
will have an economic recession

175
00:08:29,240 --> 00:08:33,180
partly from the unrest and partly from China’s
interference.

176
00:08:33,180 --> 00:08:35,560
If Hong Kong goes into a recession will

177
00:08:35,560 --> 00:08:39,050
that change people’s view on the protests?”

178
00:08:39,050 --> 00:08:40,450
Great question, Justin!

179
00:08:40,450 --> 00:08:43,810
There’s definitely a recession in Hong Kong
already.

180
00:08:43,810 --> 00:08:48,000
Tourism is down, especially from mainland
China.

181
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:50,170
And wealthy Hong Kongers are gradually transferring

182
00:08:50,170 --> 00:08:53,370
their assets from Hong Kong to overseas.

183
00:08:53,370 --> 00:08:55,610
After the first couple months of protests,

184
00:08:55,610 --> 00:08:57,990
I was also concerned that an economic recession

185
00:08:57,990 --> 00:09:01,540
would make Hong Kongers turn against the protesters.

186
00:09:01,540 --> 00:09:04,950
That’s exactly what Beijing wanted.

187
00:09:04,950 --> 00:09:06,580
And there *are* definitely people

188
00:09:06,580 --> 00:09:09,040
who are upset about the protests.

189
00:09:09,040 --> 00:09:10,470
Some of them are angry at protesters

190
00:09:10,470 --> 00:09:13,400
for hurting business and tourism.

191
00:09:13,400 --> 00:09:16,790
But a lot of Hong Kongers still put the ultimate
blame

192
00:09:16,790 --> 00:09:19,320
on the Chinese Communist Party.

193
00:09:19,320 --> 00:09:23,410
They say that if the Party hadn’t tried
to violate its agreement

194
00:09:23,410 --> 00:09:26,950
to let Hong Kong keep its freedoms until 2047,

195
00:09:26,950 --> 00:09:28,950
there would be no protests.

196
00:09:28,950 --> 00:09:31,589
That’s why huge numbers of Hong Kongers

197
00:09:31,589 --> 00:09:34,420
continue to support the protesters,

198
00:09:34,420 --> 00:09:37,330
and even join practically every week.

199
00:09:37,330 --> 00:09:39,990
And for people who were born and raised in
Hong Kong,

200
00:09:39,990 --> 00:09:43,730
they many of them believe that the alternative
to protests isn’t peace.

201
00:09:43,730 --> 00:09:47,100
It’s authoritarian rule by the Communist
Party.

202
00:09:47,100 --> 00:09:49,550
And their entire future is at stake.

203
00:09:49,550 --> 00:09:52,470
So even if they are disrupted by the protests
for now,

204
00:09:52,470 --> 00:09:56,540
not supporting the protests really isn’t
a good option.

